,"parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q06","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":6,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.1","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Types of number","qtype":"types of number","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q06","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Write 180 as a product of its prime factors.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"write"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q07","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":7,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.4","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Fractions, decimals, percentages","qtype":"fractions, decimals, percentages","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q07","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"**Without using a calculator**, work out $\\dfrac{3}{7} - \\dfrac{2}{21}$.\n\nYou must show all your working and give your answer as a fraction in its simplest form.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q08","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":8,"marks":3,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.5","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Equations","qtype":"equations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q08","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"\\[ s = \\frac{1}{2}at^2 \\]\n\n(a) Work out the value of $s$ when $a = 0.9$ and $t = 4$.\n\n(b) Rearrange the formula to find $t$ in terms of $s$ and $a$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"rearrange"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q09","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":9,"marks":2,"topics":["Number","Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.2","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Algebraic manipulation","qtype":"algebraic manipulation","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q09","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Factorise completely.\n\\[ 14xy - 7y^2 \\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"simplify"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q10","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":10,"marks":3,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.7","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Sequences","qtype":"sequences","g":"sequence","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q10","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"\\[ 22, \\quad 17, \\quad 12, \\quad 7, \\quad 2, \\quad \\ldots \\]\n\n(a) Find the next term of the sequence.\n\n(b) Find the $n$th term of the sequence.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q11","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":11,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"3.1","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q11","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Triangle $ABC$ is mathematically similar to triangle $PQR$.\n\n(a) Calculate $QR$.\n\n(b) The two triangles are the cross-sections of two mathematically similar prisms.\\\\\nThe volume of the larger prism is 320\\,cm$^3$.\n\nCalculate the volume of the smaller prism.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q12","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":12,"marks":3,"topics":["Number","Geometry"],"s":"1.11","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Ratio and proportion","qtype":"ratio and proportion","g":"proportion","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q12","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"The interior angles of a pentagon are in the ratio $4 : 5 : 5 : 7 : 9$.\n\nFind the size of the largest angle.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q13","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":13,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.8","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Standard form","qtype":"standard form","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q13","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Work out $2 \\times 10^{100} - 2 \\times 10^{98}$, giving your answer in standard form.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q14","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":14,"marks":3,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.12","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Rates","qtype":"rates","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q14","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"A train passes through a station at a speed of 108\\,km/h.\\\\\nThe length of the station is 120\\,m.\\\\\nThe train takes 7 seconds to completely pass through the station.\n\nWork out the length of the train.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q15","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":15,"marks":1,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.3","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Powers and roots","qtype":"powers and roots","g":"indices","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q15","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"\\[ 4^x = \\frac{1}{64} \\]\n\nFind the value of $x$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q16","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":16,"marks":3,"topics":["Geometry","Transformations and vectors"],"s":"4.6","d":2,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Angles","qtype":"angle calculations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q16","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Describe fully the **single** transformation that maps triangle $T$ onto triangle $P$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"describe"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q17","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":17,"marks":3,"topics":["Mensuration"],"s":"5.4","d":2,"cat":"mensuration","topic":"Surface area and volume","qtype":"surface area and volume","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q17","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Find the radius of a hemisphere of volume 80\\,cm$^3$.\n\n\\medskip\n[The volume, $V$, of a sphere with radius $r$ is $V = \\dfrac{4}{3}\\pi r^3$.]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q18","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":18,"marks":3,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Trigonometry"],"s":"3.6","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Parallel lines","qtype":"parallel lines","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q18","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"$A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ are points on a circle.\\\\\n$TU$ is a tangent to the circle at $D$.\\\\\n$DA$ is parallel to $CB$.\n\nFind the value of $x$ and the value of $y$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q19","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":19,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.6","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Parallel lines","qtype":"parallel lines","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q19","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"In the diagram, $AB$ is parallel to $PQ$.\\\\\n$AQ$ and $PB$ intersect at $X$ with $AX = XQ$.\n\nComplete the following statements.\n\n\\medskip\nIn triangles $ABX$ and $QPX$,\n\n$AX = XQ$ is given information.\n\n\\medskip\nAngle $BAX$ = Angle ... because ...\n\n\\medskip\nAngle $AXB$ = Angle ... because ...\n\n\\medskip\nTriangle $ABX$ is congruent to triangle $QPX$ because of the congruency criterion ...\n\n\\medskip\n$PX$ = ... because the triangles are congruent.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"complete"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q20","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":20,"marks":3,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.12","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Rates","qtype":"rates","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q20","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"The diagram shows the speed--time graph for 24 seconds of a car journey.\n\nCalculate\n\n(a) the deceleration of the car in the final 8 seconds,\n\n(b) the total distance travelled during the 24 seconds.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q21","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":21,"marks":2,"topics":["Number","Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.2","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Algebraic manipulation","qtype":"algebraic manipulation","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q21","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Factorise completely.\n\\[ 1 - q - a + aq \\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"simplify"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q22","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":22,"marks":2,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.2","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Algebraic manipulation","qtype":"algebraic manipulation","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q22","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Simplify fully $\\left(216y^{216}\\right)^{\\frac{2}{3}}$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"simplify"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q23","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":23,"marks":4,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q23","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"\\[ x^2 + 8x + 10 = (x + p)^2 + q \\]\n\n(a) Find the value of $p$ and the value of $q$.\n\n(b) Solve.\n\\[ x^2 + 8x + 10 = 30 \\]","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"solve"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q24","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":24,"marks":3,"topics":["Mensuration"],"s":"5.2","d":2,"cat":"mensuration","topic":"Area and perimeter","qtype":"area and perimeter","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q24","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"A cuboid measures 24\\,cm by 12\\,cm by 8\\,cm.\n\nCalculate the length of a diagonal of the cuboid.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q25","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":25,"marks":3,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.8","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Proportion","qtype":"proportion","g":"proportion","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q25","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"$w$ is proportional to the square root of $y$.\\\\\n$y$ is inversely proportional to $x$.\\\\\nWhen $x = 4$, $y = 16$ and $w = 8$.\n\nFind $w$ in terms of $x$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q26","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":26,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Transformations and vectors"],"s":"3.6","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Parallel lines","qtype":"parallel lines","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q26","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"The diagram shows a triangle $OAB$ and a parallelogram $OALK$.\\\\\nThe position vector of $A$ is $\\mathbf{a}$ and the position vector of $B$ is $\\mathbf{b}$.\\\\\n$K$ is a point on $AB$ so that $AK : KB = 1 : 2$.\n\nFind the position vector of $L$, in terms of $\\mathbf{a}$ and $\\mathbf{b}$.\\\\\nGive your answer in its simplest form.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2022MayJune-Paper21-Q27","paper":"2022MayJune-Paper21","qnum":27,"marks":4,"topics":["Algebra and graphs","Coordinate geometry"],"s":"2.8","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Proportion","qtype":"proportion","g":"proportion","src":"0580/21/M/J/22 Q27","year":2022,"session":"MayJune","tex":"The line $y = x + 1$ intersects the graph of $y = x^2 - 3x - 11$ at the points $A$ and $B$.\n\nFind the coordinates of $A$ and the coordinates of $B$.\\\\\nYou must show all your working.\n\n$A$ ( ... , ... )\n\n$B$ ( ... , ... )","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"}]